ry-beginning-search-backward=0A> To: zsh-users@sunsite.dk=0A> Date: Friday,=
 October 2, 2009, 10:48 AM=0A> Guido van Steen wrote:=0A> > * Which part of=
 the code makes sure that the commands=0A> retrieved=0A> > from history are=
 "shown" on the command line?=0A> =0A> Assigning to HISTNO moves to the giv=
en line number in the=0A> history.=A0 zsh=0A> remembers edits to history li=
nes until you hit=0A> <return> on the line you=0A> actually want to execute=
; the next time you look at the=0A> history it's=0A> back the way it was.=
=0A> =0A> > * Why does the cursor position matter, and how can one=0A> make=
 sure=0A> > that the cursor moves to the right position before the=0A> widg=
et is=0A> > invoked?=0A> =0A> As far as the widget is concerned, the cursor=
 position only=0A> matters at=0A> the start in order to find the string to =
the left which is=0A> used for the=0A> search.=A0 If you execute the widget=
 again (forward or=0A> backward) without=0A> any other command in between i=
t will use the same search=0A> string (no=0A> matter where the cursor is).=
=A0 If you move the cursor=0A> (or in fact execute=0A> any other command) a=
nd execute the widget again it will=0A> look again at=0A> the string to the=
 left.=0A> =0A> Some people like the cursor placed specially after the=0A> =
execution of=0A> history commands; this function doesn't have any support=
=0A> for that, so=0A> it's always left at the end.=0A> =0A> -- =0A> Peter S=
